M8l8th is a band that I almost never hear people talk about. M8l8th is pretty much the slavic version of Peste Noire in a way, which seems like a fitting description as this features Famine on vocals on a few songs. 

The only thing that takes getting use to is the vocals, the clean vocals are solid and fit the music, as well as the low vocals. What about the screams? Well, he sounds like a Banshee taking off, but you get used to it, maybe...

The main thing with this record is the fact that these guys are unreal musicians. The music sounds fucking incredible in my opinion... 

If you like KPN definitely give these guys a chance..

#nowplaying 

Hails.

Most importantly theyâ€™re a really good group of people. Although Iâ€™ve yet to train with them, theyâ€™re always really welcoming when I turn up, normally last-minute ğŸ˜…, at the events and they have a good social calendar. At their Christmas Party last year, they kindly started a collection for  Run2Ukraine.

I would like to thank Portslade Hedgehoppers for an incredible donation of Â£250 that was made last week. 

If anyone is looking for a good running club to join let me know or contact them directly. No. 1540 ("Laughing in the face of love")

Well, I was standing at the corner when I heard it on the radio.
The newsman told the people, "Four minutes to go!"
He said you don't have to worry but you better run for cover fast
Because the reds are a-coming and they're looking for you to blast.

...

Well, everybody was screaming as we ran to the shelter zone.
I heard a man cry, "Lord above, save my soul!"
I saw a mother and her baby crash down on the ground,
And a priest was dying to be saved from the death of clowns.

I thought I was going insane,
I thought I was going insane!
There's only four minutes left of oxygen to my brain.

Nightmare Zero hit the town,
Nightmare Zero mushroom cloud.
We're laughing in the face of love.
Soon they'll be nothing above.
Pretty baby walkin', pretty baby talkin' ...
Pretty soon they gonna be dead.

-- from The Motors, "Nightmare Zero", TENEMENT STEPS

This banknote was issued for the 30th anniversary of Ukraine's independence, which was declared on August 24, 1991. Since Ukraine's independence, the country has experienced many challenges and changes, both in economy, politics, and diplomacy. This banknote commemorates the 30th anniversary of this great nation.
The obverse features Ukrainian scientist, philosopher, and naturalist Volodymyr Vernadskyi (1863-1945). He was the founder of the scientific fields of geochemistry, biogeochemistry, and radiogeology, and also one of the founders and the first president of the Ukrainian Academy of Sciences, established in 1918. His famous quote "I believe in the great future of Ukraine" is also depicted.
The reverse shows the Presidium building of the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, which was built in the 1850s according to a design by architect Alexander Beretti. The building's facade is decorated with rustication and an attic decorative element, as well as a cast-iron grid.

Posts featuring Chucks are usually pretty lighthearted, but this is a little different. I ask you to turn your attention to the socks that I picked up at @leftfieldnyc this past weekend. I liked the colors, but when I learned that profits from the sale of them went to helping the people of the Ukraine, I knew I had to have them.

The enormity of the crimes being committed by Putin and his henchmen cannot be underestimated. Millions of people have been driven from their homes, and thousands of innocent people have been killed. It is sickening and profoundly distressing, and all too many people of conscience feel powerless to do anything about it.

As fate would have it, I am reading a book on the life of composer Claude Debussy. I am near the end, when the composer was stricken with cancer, running out of money, and forced to abandon his home in Paris by the advancing German army. He wrote to a friend something that rings all too true today: 

â€œSo when will all this hatred end? And even in this business is it really a question of hatred? When will they stop entrusting the destiny of nations to people who regard humanity as a means of self-advancement?â€ 

Debussyâ€™s response to the horror he experienced was to write music of timeless and transcendent beauty.  However modest or great our contribution, we must all remain determined to keep the spirt of hope alive and our commitment to the pursuit of peace and justice for all a non-negotiable element of our humanity.

Ukrainian soldier who lost his leg at the front ran the London Marathon. Roman Kashpur covered 42 kilometers on a prosthesis, raising funds to help wounded defenders of Ukraine.

Roman lost his leg in 2019 due to a detonation on an enemy mine, but this does not stop him from setting records and inspiring others. Kashpur went to defend his Motherland in the east when he was still 19 years old, at the age of 22 the scout lost a limb near Maryinka. After that, he found himself in sports.

The Ukrainian defender showed everyone that the Ukrainian people are strong and never give up.
